 holds the annual Frederick William Atherton Lecture (since 1966) on ethical and social criticism. Great-great-great-grandson of Jonathan Edwards."}],"slug":"frederick-atherton-1865"},"HD2067":{"id":"HD2067","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":9,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"X00665","mother_id":"HD2064"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1868},"death":{"year":1917},"gender":"male","marriages":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Edward Dwight Atherton","first_name":"Edward","last_name":"Atherton","middle_name":"Dwight","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"edward-atherton-1868"},"HD2068":{"id":"HD2068","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":9,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"X00665","mother_id":"HD2064"},"tags":["academic"],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1871,"month":9,"day":25},"death":{"year":1944,"month":3,"day":8},"gender":"male","notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"Composer trained by the leading European masters","detail":"Set music to the poems of Charlotte Perkins Gilman. Where his brother Frederick legacy is a Harvard lecture series, Percy is a $15,000 Harvard scholarship fund for musical talent — the two brothers embodying the Dwight family twin traditions of public life and the arts. (Wikipedia)","body":"Studied composition under three of the most eminent Gilded Age European teachers, composing songs, chamber music, and comic operas from his lifelong Boston home.","number":1},{"number":2,"category":"arts","header":"He set Charlotte Perkins Gilman to music","body":"Atherton composed songs, chamber works, and comic operas, and set the poems of feminist writer Charlotte Perkins Gilman — their correspondence survives at Harvard. He never married, living his whole life at 144 Commonwealth Avenue."},{"number":3,"category":"arts","header":"He left Harvard a scholarship for musicians","body":"His will endowed a $15,000 Harvard fund for musically gifted students and gave $1,000 to the Library of Congress music division. He had trained under the great European masters — Rheinberger in Munich, Sgambati in Rome, Widor in Paris."}],"marriages":[],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Percy Lee Atherton","first_name":"Percy","last_name":"Atherton","middle_name":"Lee","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1893"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"education":[{"school_name":"Harvard College","dates":"1893","type":"undergraduate","notes":"honors in music"}],"career":[{"role":"Composer","notes":"songs, chamber music, comic operas"}],"slug":"percy-atherton-1871"},"HD2069":{"id":"HD2069","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"HD2051","mother_id":"X00662"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1841,"month":3,"day":13,"city":"New York","state":"New York"},"death":{"year":1921,"month":5,"day":19,"city":"Brooklyn","state":"New York"},"orbit_connections":[{"name":"Rossiter Worthington Raymond","relationship":"Husband of Sarah Mellen Dwight (HD2073)","notes":"Rossiter Worthington Raymond (Apr 27, 1840 Cincinnati OH - Dec 31, 1918 Brooklyn NY). Mining engineer, legal scholar, author, Civil War officer, chess player, poet. Described at his memorial as one of the most remarkable cases of versatility that our country has ever seen. Aide-de-camp to General Fremont during the Civil War; commended for gallant conduct. US Commissioner of Mining Statistics. Secretary of AIME 1884-1911 (AIME named its Rossiter W. Raymond Memorial Award after him in 1945). Raymond Peak (10,014 ft), Alpine County CA, named for him in 1865. His parents participated in the Underground Railroad in Syracuse NY. Member of the American Philosophical Society. Famous quote: Life is eternal; and love is immortal; and death is only a horizon; and a horizon is nothing save the limit of our sight. Published Western novel Brave Hearts (1873). Buried Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn. (Wikipedia; FindAGrave)","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rossiter_W._Raymond","connection_type":"orbit_spouse"}],"gender":"female","marriages":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Mellen Dwight","first_name":"Sarah","middle_name":"Mellen","maiden_name":"Dwight","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"sarah-dwight-1841"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{"INST018":{"id":"INST018","primary_name":"Amherst College","name":"Amherst College","short_name":"Amherst","alt_names":[],"type":"university","founding_year":1821,"location":{"city":"Amherst","state":"Massachusetts"},"primary_persons":[],"hooker_connected_people":["HD0873","HD1687","HD1758","HD1759","HD1861","HD2152","HD2525","HD2559","HD3048","I00191","HD5928"],"person_ids":["X00600","X0066